    <text id="R12949667T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Confederate Assistant Adjutant Giles Cooke writes to Colonel McCausland informing
                    him of Lee's August, 1863, orders that Jenkins' and Wharton's brigades report to
                    General Samuel Jones in Warm Springs via Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    HDQRS. DEPARTMENT OF WESTERN VIRGINIA,
                    <name type="recipient">Col. McCAUSLAND,<lb/> Cmdg., &amp;c., Princeton:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1863-08-24">August 24, 1863.</date>
                        <name type="place">Dublin,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>Telegrams, dated Union, August 23 and 24 inform me that the enemy, reported 3,000
                    strong, have pressed Col. Jackson back toward Warm Springs, and that a body of
                    cavalry numbering 1,200 may make a raid on the railroad near New River Bridge;
                    that another heavy column is moving on Lewisburg.</p>
                <p>In view of the above, Gen. Lee has ordered Wharton's and Jenkins' brigades to
                    report to Gen. Jones, via Staunton and Warm Springs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>GILES B. COOKE,<lb/> Assistant Adjutant and Inspector Gen.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
